{{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Alejandro Felipe Paula |honorific-suffix = |image = |imagesize = |smallimage = |caption = |order = |office = [[List of Prime Ministers of the Netherlands Antilles|Prime Minister of the Netherlands Antilles]] |term_start1 = 28 December 1993 |term_end1 = 31 March 1994 |monarch1 = [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Beatrix]] |governor1 = [[Jaime Saleh]] |predecessor1 = [[Suzanne Camelia-Römer]] |successor1 = {{Interlanguage link multi|Miguel Pourier|nl}} |birth_date = {{Birth date|1937|5|2}} |birth_place = [[Curaçao]] |death_date = {{death date and age |2018|08|13 |1937|05|02 |mf=yes}} |birthname = |nationality = [[Dutch nationality|Dutch]] |party = |otherparty = |spouse = |partner = |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = |profession = |cabinet = |religion = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }} '''Alejandro Felipe Paula''' also known as '''Jandi Paula''' (May 2, 1937 - Aug 13, 2018) was a [[Curaçao]]an academic, historian and politician. He served as [[List of Prime Ministers of the Netherlands Antilles|Prime Minister of the Netherlands Antilles]] from 28 December 1993 to 31 March 1994. Paula was director of the National Archive of the Netherlands Antilles between 1969 and 1989. He also was a professor and rector at the [[University of Curaçao|University of the Netherlands Antilles]] in the 1990s.
==Career== Paula was born on [[Curaçao]] on 2 May 1937.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.scribd.com/author/311888263/Alejandro-Jandie-Paula# |title=Alejandro "Jandie" Paula |publisher=Scribd |date= |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> He was partially schooled in Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sharlon Monart |url=http://archief.wereldomroep.nl/caribiana/article/nieuwe-naam-peter-stuyvesant-college-bekend?page=1 |title=Nieuwe naam Peter Stuyvesant College bekend |publisher=Wereldomroep |date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> Paula later studied in the Netherlands, the Dominican Republic and Italy. After the [[1969 Curaçao uprising]] Paula served on the Rebuilding commission and the investigationary commission. He served as chair of the latter commission but resigned after being threatened.<ref name="Oostindie1999">{{cite book|author=Gert Oostindie|title=Curaçao, 30 mei 1969: verhalen over de revolte|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ofaqHobHvPIC&pg=PA94|year=1999|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|isbn=978-90-5356-372-4|pages=94–}}</ref>
Paula served as director of the National Archive of the Netherlands Antilles between 1969 and 1989.<ref name=vers>{{cite web |author=Leoni Leidel-Schenk |url=http://www.versgeperst.com/nieuws/95374/alejandro-paula-%E2%80%98zeer-vereerd%E2%80%99.html |title=Alejandro Paula zeer vereerd |language=Dutch |publisher=Versgeperst.com |date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=14 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220122252/http://www.versgeperst.com/nieuws/95374/alejandro-paula-%E2%80%98zeer-vereerd%E2%80%99.html |archive-date=2016-12-20 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Paula was a lecturer, and later professor, of sociology, philosophy and human rights at the [[University of Curaçao|University of the Netherlands Antilles]] from 1990 to 2000. In his last three years he served as [[Rector (academia)|rector magnificus]].<ref name=vers/>
On [[Curaçao status referendum, 1993|19 November 1993 a Curaçao status referendum]] was held. With the outcome in opposition to what she had campaigned for, Prime Minister [[Maria Liberia Peters]] resigned. She was succeeded by [[Suzanne Camelia-Römer]]. Paula was appointed as [[formateur]] by [[Governor of the Netherlands Antilles]], [[Jaime Saleh]]. He managed to form a coalition government which would rule until a government would be formed after the [[Netherlands Antilles general election, 1994|February 1994 general election]].<ref name="Group2004">{{cite book|author=Taylor & Francis Group|title=The Europa World Year: Kazakhstan – Zimbabwe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gP_-8rXzQs8C&pg=PA3099|year=2004|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-85743-255-8|pages=3099–}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Maria Liberia Peters |url=http://antilliaansdagblad.com/index.php/curacao/lezers/2855-to-set-the-record-straight |title=To set the record straight |language=Dutch |publisher=''Antilliaans Dagblad'' |date=30 March 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> Paula himself served as [[List of Prime Ministers of the Netherlands Antilles|Prime Minister of the Netherlands Antilles]]. His government was sworn in on 28 December 1993.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/1993/12/27/interim-kabinet-op-antillen-7208231-a1206402 |title=Interim-kabinet op Antillen |language=Dutch |publisher=''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' |date=27 December 1993 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> He was succeeded when the government of {{Interlanguage link multi|Miguel Pourier|nl}} was installed on 31 March 1994.<ref name="BanksDay2016">{{cite book|editor1=Arthur S. Banks |editor2=Thomas C. Muller |title=Political Handbook of the World 1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6mFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA660|date=1 February 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-349-14951-3|pages=660–}}</ref>
==Personal life== Paula married a woman from [[Trinidad]] in 1966. The couple has two children.<ref name="Oostindie1999"/> In 2011 the Peter Stuyvesant College was renamed in Paula's honour.<ref name=vers/>. Paula passed away on August 13, 2018 due to health complications.
==Works== * ''Slavery in a Nutshell'' (1987) * ''Hoofdmomenten uit de staatkundige ontwikkeling van de Nederlandse Antillen'' (1989) * ''1795: De slavenopstand op Curaçao'' (1994) * ''The Cry of My Life'' (2005)
