{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox film | name = The Restorers | image = The Restorers cover art.jpg | alt = | caption = Cover art | director = Adam N. White | producer = Hemlock Films | writer = Adam N. White | starring = | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = Hemlock Films | distributor = | released = {{Film date|2003|07|19}} | runtime = 60 minutes | country = United States | language = English | budget = | gross = }} '''''The Restorers''''' (sometimes referred to as '''''The Restorers: Giving History a Future...''''') is a 2003 documentary film by Adam White about [[vehicle restoration|restoration]] of vintage war planes ranging from the [[F4U Corsair]] to the [[B-17]] "Yankee Lady". White interviewed dozens of people who have dedicated much of their lives and thousands of dollars to restore planes for museums, [[air show]]s, or their own personal collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-restorers-290083|title=The Restorers|accessdate=January 1, 2010|work=[[Allmovie]]}}</ref> The subjects range from people who restore planes in their own garages to major corporations; the end results range from planes that are used in exhibitions and air shows to planes that are restored as racing vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0411804/plotsummary|title=Plot Summary for The Restorers (2004) |accessdate=January 1, 2010|publisher=[[IMDb.com]]}}</ref>
In 2005, White earned a regional 2004 [[Emmy Award]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=118015EBB772DAD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=WSU Graduate's Tuskegee Airmen Documentary To Get Dayton Launch|accessdate=January 1, 2010|date=March 16, 2007|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|author=Larsen, Dave|page=GO29}}</ref> The film had been released July 18&ndash;20, 2003 at the Neon Movies in [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]], Ohio in conjunction with the Vectren Dayton Air Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FC3ED1F6F58272C&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=5 Things You Need To Know This Week For Next Week|accessdate=January 1, 2010|date=July 11, 2003|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|author=|page=14, GO! section}}</ref> In February 2004, the film was made available in both [[DVD]] and [[VHS]] format. On March 3, 2004 it was screened at the Fargo Film Festival where it won Documentary Feature Runner-Up award. It debuted on television on [[Western Reserve Public Media]] April 13, 2004 and was reaired on June 16. The [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) broadcast made the film eligible for the 2004 Best Special Programming regional Emmy Award by the Cleveland Regional chapter of the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]], which it won. The film had limited national PBS broadcasts in 2006 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therestorers.com/html/news.html|title=The Restorers: Giving History a Future...: News|publisher=Hemlock films}}</ref> While producing this film, White stumbled upon the restoration efforts of the [[Red Tail Project]], which led to the production of ''[[Red Tail Reborn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/redtailreborn/|title=Red Tail Reborn|accessdate=January 1, 2010|publisher=[[Public Broadcast Service]]/Hemlock Films}}</ref>
